label.value: abnormal ascending aorta and coronary artery attachment

value.value: any anomaly of the connection site of any or all of the coronary arteries to the ascending aorta
widening or enlargment of the lumen of the descending aorta
underdevelopment or reduced size of the descending aorta, usually due to reduced cell number

label.value: anomalous pulmonary origin of left coronary artery

value.value: the left coronary artery arises from the pulmonary artery insead of the aorta

definition.value: "anomalous" was used in the term name instead of "abnormal" due to common usage of this term among cardiologists.

value.value: an abnormal communication between the terminus of a coronary artery, bypassing the myocardial capillary bed and entering either a chamber of the heart (coronary-cameral fistula) or any segment of the systemic or pulmonary circulation (coronary arteriovenous fistula)
a protruding sac formed by the dilation of the wall of a coronary artery resulting from a weakening of the vessel wall
a protruding sac within the cranial space formed by the dilation of the wall of an artery or a vein resulting from a weakening of the vessel wall
a protruding sac within the brain formed by the dilation of the wall of an artery or a vein resulting from a weakening of the vessel wall
abnormal communications between the pulmonary arteries and the pulmonary veins, or between a bronchial artery and the pulmonary vein
an abnormal communication between the left ventricle and the ascending aorta in addition to the aortic valve

any structural anomaly of the spaces betwen the superior aspect of each of the three cusps of the aortic valve and the dilated portion of the wall of the ascending aorta, immediately above each cusp; the three sinuses include the posterior (non-coronary sinus), and the right and left aortic sinuses (from which the left and right coronary arteries arise)
a protruding sac formed by the dilation of the wall of the aortic sinus resulting from a weakening of the vessel wall
the presence of two cusps in the aortic valve instead of three
underdevelopment or reduced size of the aortic arch, usually due to reduced cell number
absence of one of the two subclavian arteries; the right subclavian artery normally extends from the brachiocephalic artery to the right side of the body
any structural anomaly of the artery that normally extends from the brachiocephalic artery to the right side of the body
any structural anomaly of the artery that extends from the aortic arch to the left side of the body

label.value: abnormal heart atrium auricular region morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the small conical pouch projections located on the upper anterior portion of each atrium of the heart

label.value: abnormal inferior vena cava valve morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the semicircular fold of endocardium located on the right atrium at the point of attachment of the inferior vena cava

any structural anomaly of the semicircular fold of the right atrial endocardium located at the coronary sinus attachment to the right atrium that serves to prevent the reflux of blood back to the coronary arteries during atrial contraction
any structural anomaly of the thin serous membrane, primarily composed of endothelial tissue, that lines the interior of the atria
any structural anomaly of the atrial part of middle layer of the heart, comprised of involuntary muscle
any structural anomaly of the thin serous membrane, primarily composed of endothelial tissue, that lines the interior of the ventricles
any structural anomaly of the vertical crest of the interior wall of the right atrium that lies to the right of the sinus of the vena cava and separates this from the remainder of the right atrium
any structural anomaly of the prominent ridges of atrial myocardium located on the inner surface of most of the right atrium and both the right and left auricular regions
any structural anomaly of the portion of the cavity of the right atrium of the heart that receives the blood from the vena cavae and is separated from the rest of the atrium by the crista terminalis

label.value: abnormal interventricular septum muscular part morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the muscular portion of the wall between the two lower chambers of the heart
any structural anomaly of the ventricular part of middle layer of the heart, comprised of involuntary muscle
underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, of the heart myocardium
underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, of the atrial part of the heart myocardium
underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, of the ventricular part of the heart myocardium
underdevelopment or reduced size of the supporting bundles of muscular fibers lining the walls of the heart, usually due to a reduced number of cells
anomaly in the length of the interval between an R wave and the next R wave; the RR interval is the inverse of the heart rate
any anomaly in the T wave which is normally caused by the repolarization (or recovery) of the ventricles
increase in the length of the interval between an R wave and the next R wave; the RR interval is the inverse of the heart rate
reduction in the length of the interval between an R wave and the next R wave; the RR interval is the inverse of the heart rate

any anomaly in the pattern of the graphic record of the integrated action currents of the cardiac cycle represented as changes in voltage; the prominent waves in the ECG correspond to specific conduction activity in areas of the heart and the timing and amplitude of ECG waveforms provide valuable information about heart rate and rhythm
reduction in the size (height or maximum displacement) of the P wave
absence of the P wave which represents atrial depolarization and corresponds to electrical impulses rather than mechanical atria contractions

decrease in the length of time between the beginning of atrial depolarization and the beginning of ventricular depolarization, measured by the interval from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex

absence of the ECG segment representing the length of time between the beginning of atrial depolarization and the beginning of ventricular depolarization, measured by the interval from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex
any anomaly in the length of time from the beginning of the Q wave to the peak of the R wave
changes in QRS waveform pattern including different RSR' patterns, additional R waves, notched or absent Q or S wave, or more than one R wave
any anomaly in the downward deflection in the ECG occurring after the PR interval that represents depolarization of the interventricular septum
absence of the downward deflection in the ECG occurring after the PR interval that represents depolarization of the interventricular septum
any structural anomaly of the impulse conduction tract that originates in the sinoatrial node and transmits signal to the left atrium

definition.value: According to Stedman's Medical Dictionary, the anatomic reality of this structure has been disputed.

value.value: a partial or complete obstruction of the impulse that originates in the atria or sinoatrial node from reaching or transmitting through the atrioventricular node to the ventricles
a partial or complete obstruction of the impulse leaving the sinoatrial node preventing it from activating atrial muscle
absence of the artery that arises from the right ventricle and conveys unaerated blood to the lungs
pathologic deposition of calcium salts in the aorta
